# Session 1 — Node.js & Express Notes
> Topics covered: Raw Node HTTP server · Express routing · Middleware · POST requests · Data validation · JSON responses

---

## 1. What is Node.js?

Node.js is **JavaScript that runs on your computer/server — not in the browser.**

It takes the same V8 engine Chrome uses and puts it on your machine so you can run JS anywhere.

| Browser JS | Node.js |
|---|---|
| ❌ Read/write files | ✅ Read/write files |
| ❌ Access database | ✅ Access database |
| ❌ Hide secret keys | ✅ Keep API keys secret |
| ❌ Be a server | ✅ BE the server |

---

## 2. require vs import

```js
// React style (modern ES6)
import express from 'express'

// Node style (CommonJS - older but very common)
const express = require('express')
```

Same idea — both bring a module into your file. `require` is Node's older way.

**Built-in modules** (no install needed): `fs`, `path`, `http`, `os`
**npm packages** (need to install): `express`, `axios`, `mongoose`

Think of it like a phone:
- Built-in modules = apps that come with your phone (camera, calculator)
- npm packages = apps you download from Play Store

---

## 3. The File System Module (fs)

```js
const fs = require('fs')

// Create/write a file
fs.writeFileSync('hello.txt', 'Hello from Node.js!')

// Read a file
const data = fs.readFileSync('hello.txt', 'utf8')
console.log(data)
```

Your JavaScript can now **create real files on your computer** — this is not possible in the browser.

---

## 4. Raw HTTP Server (Node without Express)

```js
const http = require('http')

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  if (req.url === '/') {
    res.write("Welcome home!")
  } else if (req.url === '/about') {
    res.write("This is the about page")
  } else {
    res.write("Page not found")
  }
  res.end()
})

server.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log("Server running on port 3000")
})
```

Key concepts:
- `req.url` — which path the user visited (`/`, `/about` etc.)
- `req.method` — what type of request (GET, POST etc.)
- `res.write()` — write a response
- `res.end()` — finish the response
- `server.listen(3000)` — start the server on port 3000

**localhost** = this machine itself (not the internet)
**Port 3000** = like a flat number in an apartment building — multiple servers on same machine use different ports

---

## 5. Why Express?

Raw Node routing with if/else becomes a nightmare for real apps:

```js
// Raw Node — gets messy fast 😬
if (req.url === '/') { ... }
else if (req.url === '/about') { ... }
else if (req.url === '/contact') { ... }
// imagine 50 more routes...
```

Express makes this clean, readable, and powerful.

---

## 6. Express Basics

### Setup
```bash
npm init -y
npm install express
```

### Basic server
```js
const express = require('express')
const app = express()

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send("Hello from Express!")
})

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log("Express server running on port 3000")
})
```

### res.send() vs res.json()
```js
res.send("Hello")           // plain text
res.json({ name: "Rahul" }) // JSON — used for APIs
```

### HTTP Methods
```
GET    → fetch/read data    → app.get()
POST   → send/submit data   → app.post()
PUT    → update data        → app.put()
DELETE → delete data        → app.delete()
```

---

## 7. Middleware

Middleware is code that runs **before every request reaches your route** — like a security guard at a mall entrance.

```js
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  console.log(req.method, req.url, new Date())
  next() // MUST call next() or request freezes forever!
})
```

Key rules:
- `app.use()` must be placed **above** your routes
- Always call `next()` when done — otherwise the request hangs
- Runs for **every** request automatically

**Real world uses of middleware:**
- Logging (what we built)
- Authentication checks (is user logged in?)
- Parsing request body (express.json())
- Error handling

### Logger middleware we built
```js
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  console.log(req.method, req.url, new Date())
  next()
})
```

---

## 8. POST Requests & req.body

To receive data from frontend (forms, React apps etc.):

```js
// MUST add this middleware to read JSON body
app.use(express.json())

app.post('/register', (req, res) => {
  console.log(req.body) // { name: "Rahul", email: "rahul@gmail.com" }
  res.json({ message: "User registered!" })
})
```

Without `app.use(express.json())`, `req.body` will be `undefined`!

---

## 9. Data Validation

Always validate data before saving to database:

```js
app.post('/register', (req, res) => {
  if (!req.body.name || !req.body.email) {
    return res.json({ message: "Name and email are required!" })
  }
  res.json({ message: "User registered!", user: req.body })
})
```

---

## 10. HTTP Status Codes

```
200 → OK (success)
201 → Created (something was saved)
400 → Bad request (user sent wrong data)
404 → Not found
500 → Server error
```

Usage (coming next session):
```js
res.status(400).json({ error: "Name and email are required" })
res.status(201).json({ message: "User registered!" })
```

---

## 11. JS Concepts Revised

### Async/Await & Event Loop
```js
async function getUser() {
  console.log("A")
  const data = await fetch("https://api.example.com/user")
  console.log("B")
}

getUser()
console.log("C")

// Output: A → C → B
// await pauses that function but doesn't block everything else
```

### Higher Order Functions
A function that takes another function as an argument (or returns one).

```js
// All of these are higher order functions:
[1,2,3].map(num => num * 2)
setTimeout(() => console.log("hi"), 1000)
app.use((req, res, next) => {})
```

Middleware in Express is a perfect example of a higher order function — `app.use()` takes your function and calls it on every request.

---

## 12. Full server.js so far

```js
const express = require('express')
const app = express()

// Middleware
app.use(express.json())

app.use((req, res, next) => {
  console.log(req.method, req.url, new Date())
  next()
})

// Routes
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send("Hello from Express!")
})

app.get('/about', (req, res) => {
  res.send("Hello from about")
})

app.get('/contact', (req, res) => {
  res.send("Hello from contact")
})

app.get('/user', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ name: "Diya", age: 20, city: "Jaipur" })
})

app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: "ab" },
    { id: 2, name: "cd" }
  ])
})

app.post('/register', (req, res) => {
  if (!req.body.name || !req.body.email) {
    return res.json({ message: "Name and email are required!" })
  }
  res.json({ message: "User registered!" })
})

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log("Express server running on port 3000")
})
```

